  <title>
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">Response to the Victims of Floods and support to COVID-19 awareness in Rwanda</narrative>
  </title>
  <description type="1">
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">This 45 days project implementation period will be appropriate for the immediate needs while the medium to long term needs arising from the floods damage are being planned for and additional resources mobilised under the coordination of the government. This response will also provide a complimentary response to the food assistance currently under way to meet the immediate gaps. Moreover, as Rwanda continues the fight of COVID  -19, the project will be instrumental to mitigate the spread of COVID  -19 for the affected population as it will allow targeted households to go to their homes, and leave temporary shelter where conditions are not conducive to required hygiene and social distancing for COVID -19 prevention.  Based on the identified needs and the proposed funding amount, this project prioritizes the basic lifesaving responses:   1. Shelter:  Distribution of basic construction materials such as  iron sheets and  galvanized wires.                                                                                                                                       2. Non -food Items (NFIs): Distribution of critical and strategic NFIs such as Blankets, Mats, Jerricans, Bathing soap, Washing soap, Buckets, Pads, Tooth brushes, Tooth Pastes, Saucepans, Plates, Cups and Folks.  3.WASH: The will  intervention will ensure that the floods victims have access to the basic m basic hygiene and sanitation items.    The project will also contibute to the beneficiaries&apos; hygiene behaviour change towards disaster and COVID -19, contributing to the ongoing efforts on DRR and COVID -19 awareness.This includes early floods warnign messaging  and COVID -19 wareness among the affected population and targeted Districts. This project component will work with pre -existing disaster risk reduction structures in the communities to intensify DRR and COVID -19 awareness.</narrative>
  </description>
